Q1. Optimal design.¶

Create candidate design points, using dummy coding for factors.

In [21]:
I = 3; J = 4
C = zeros(I * J, I - 1 + J)
row = 1
dummyI = zeros(1, I - 1)
dummyJ = zeros(1, J - 1)
for i = 1:I
    for j = 1:J
        # Intercept
        C[row, 1] = 1.0
        # Dummy coding for factor 1
        fill!(dummyI, 0.0)
        if i > 1
            dummyI[i - 1] = 1.0
        end
        C[row, 2:I] = dummyI
        # Dummy coding for factor 2
        fill!(dummyJ, 0.0)
        if j > 1
            dummyJ[j - 1] = 1.0
        end
        C[row, I+1:end] = dummyJ
        # Increase row index
        row += 1
    end
end

Q3. Best subset regression on the prostate cancer data¶

Read in the prostate cancer data.

In [26]:
prostate = readdlm("prostate.txt", '\t'; header=true)
X = float64(prostate[1][:, 2:9])
y = float64(prostate[1][:, 10])
trainidx = (prostate[1][:, 11] .== "T");

Standardize predictors and add intercept.

In [27]:

X = X ./ std(X, 1)
X = [ones(size(X, 1), 1) X];

Train/test split.

In [28]:
Xtr = X[trainidx, :]
ytr = y[trainidx]
Xte = X[~trainidx, :]
yte = y[~trainidx];

Solve a sequence of best subset regressions. The function lsqbestsubset is implemented via the JuMP.jl package because of its capability to incoporate SOS1 constraints.

In [29]:
include("hw6.jl")
# Use Gurobi solver becoz it accepts SOS constraints
using Gurobi
solver = GurobiSolver(OutputFlag=1)
set_default_solver(solver)

klist = 0:8
βhat_path = zeros(size(Xtr, 2), length(klist))
err_path = zeros(1, length(klist))
aic_path = zeros(1, length(klist))
bic_path = zeros(1, length(klist))
n = length(ytr)
@time for i = 1:length(klist)
    βhat_path[:, i] = lsqbestsubset(ytr, Xtr, klist[i])
    err_path[i] = norm(yte - Xte * βhat_path[:, i])^2 / length(yte)
    aic_path[i] = 2.0n * log(norm(ytr - Xtr * βhat_path[:, i])) + 
        2.0 * (log(2.0π) + 1.0) + 2.0 * countnz(βhat_path[:, i])
    bic_path[i] = 2.0n * log(norm(ytr - Xtr * βhat_path[:, i])) + 
        2.0 * (log(2.0π) + 1.0) + log(n) * countnz(βhat_path[:, i])
end

#
# This function computes optimal design ('D', 'A', 'E') on the
# candidate design points in the rows of C.
#
function optimdesign(C::Matrix{Float64}; design::Char='D')

  # Number of candidate points
  m = size(C, 1)

  # Create optimization variables
  prob = Convex.Variable(m)
  # Set up optmization problem using Convex.jl
  if design == 'D'
    problem = maximize(logdet(C' * diagm(prob) * C))
  elseif design == 'E'
    problem = maximize(lambda_min(C' * diagm(prob) * C))
  elseif design == 'A'
    B = Convex.Semidefinite(size(C, 2))
    problem = minimize(trace(B))
    problem.constraints += isposdef([B eye(size(C, 2)); eye(size(C, 2)) C' * diagm(prob) * C])
  end
  problem.constraints += prob >= 0.0
  problem.constraints += sum(prob) == 1.0
  # Solve the problem by calling solve
  solve!(problem)
  # Return
  prob.value

end


#
# This function finds the best model with size <= k (excluding intercept)
#
function lsqbestsubset(y::Vector{Float64}, X::Matrix{Float64}, k::Int)

  # Dimension
  n = length(y)
  p = size(X, 2) - 1
  # Check validity of k
  if k < 0 || k > p
    error("Model size should be in [0, p]")
  end

  # Gurobi environment
  m = Model(solver=GurobiSolver(OutputFlag=0))
  # Create optimization variables
  @defVar(m, res[1:n])   # r = y - X * βhat
  @defVar(m, βhat[1:p+1])
  @defVar(m, z[1:p], Bin)     # z = 1{βhat==0}
  # Quadratic objective
  @setObjective(m, Min, sum{res[i] * res[i], i=1:n})
  # Equality constraint r = y - X * βhat
  for i = 1:n
    @addConstraint(m, res[i] + sum{X[i, j] * βhat[j], j=1:p+1} == y[i])
  end
  # SOS constraint
  for j = 1:p
    addSOS1(m, [βhat[j+1], z[j]])
  end
  # Cardinality constraint
  @addConstraint(m, sum{z[j], j=1:p} >= p - k)

  # Solve the problem by calling solve
  #display(m)
  status = solve(m)
  # Return
  bhat = zeros(p+1)
  for j = 1:p+1
    @inbounds bhat[j] = getValue(βhat[j])
  end
  bhat

end

#
# This function completes a matrix Y by minimizing nuclear norm of X subject to
# the constraint that X[i, j] = Y[i, j] for observed entries (i, j).
#
function matcomp(Y::Matrix{Float64}; mischar::Float64=0.0)

  # Linear indices of obs. entries
  obsidx = find(Y .≠ mischar)

  # Create optimization variables
  X = Convex.Variable(size(Y))
  # Set up optmization problem
  problem = minimize(nuclear_norm(X))
  problem.constraints += X[obsidx] == Y[obsidx]
  # Solve the problem by calling solve
  solve!(problem)
  # Return
  X.value

end

#
# This function computes a strength score for each team based on the
# win-loss data in input matrix W. W[i, j] is the observed wins of
# team i over team j. Diagonal entries should be 0.
#
function rankteam(W::Matrix{Float64}; model::String="BradleyTerry")

  # Number of teams
  p::Int = size(W, 1)

  if model == "BradleyTerry"
    # Set up optmization problem
    logs = Convex.Variable(p)
    obj = 0.0
    for i = 1:p
      for j = 1:p
        obj += W[i, j] * (logs[i] - Convex.logsumexp([logs[i], logs[j]]))
      end
    end
    problem = maximize(obj)
    # Solve the problem
    solve!(problem)
    s = exp(logs.value)
    return s / sum(s)

  elseif model == "Normal"

    # Create optimization variables
    s = Convex.Variable(p)
    a = sqrt( [ 0.018102332171520
               0.011338501342044
               0.072727608432177
               0.184816581789135
               0.189354610912339
               0.023660365352785 ] )
    b = [3.0, 2.5, 2.0, 1.0, -1.0, -2.0]
    obj = 0.0
    for i = 1:p
      for j = 1:p
        if i ≠ j
          obj += W[i, j] * sum_squares(pos(a .* (b - (s[i] - s[j]))))
        end
      end
    end
    problem = Convex.minimize(obj)
    problem.constraints += s >= 0.0
    problem.constraints += s <= 1.0
    # Solve the problem by calling solve
    solve!(problem)
    return s.value / sum(s.value)

  end

end
